<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="fun4-reading" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>FUN-4 Reading</title>
    <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li> <p>Things you should understand and know:
        <ul>
            <li>Recognize parametric equations for a space curve</li>
            <li>Define the limit of a vector-valued function</li>
            <li>Limits, derivatives, and integrals of vector functions</li>
            <li>The significance of a unit tangent vector</li>
            <li>A particle's path in space determined by a vector function</li>
            <li>Define normal and binormal vectors</li>
            <li>Define the tangential and normal components of acceleration</li>
        </ul></p>
        <p>Things you should be able to do:
        <ul>
            <li>Write the general equation of a vector-valued function in component format and unit-vector form</li>
            <li>Find the derivative of a vector function</li>
            <li>Find the tangent vector at a point for a position vector</li>
            <li>Find the definite integral of a vector function</li>
            <li>Find the length of a particle's path</li>
            <li>Calculate the curvature of a curve in space</li>
            <li>Find the velocity and acceleration vectors of a particle moving in space</li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
      <li><p>You will be assessed on the following criteria:
        <ul>
          <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
              that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
          <li><p>Vector function notation: Use correct notation for vector functions, including component 
            format and unit-vector form.</p></li>
          <li><p>Derivatives of Vector Functions: Find the derivative of a vector function, interpret its meaning, 
            and apply it to problems.</p></li>
          <li><p>Integrals of Vector Functions: Find the definite integral of a vector function, interpret its meaning, 
            and apply it to problems.</p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>
        <p>All of the readings for this course come from the OpenStax Calculus 
            Volume 3 textbook, which is available for free online at 
            <url href="https://openstax.org/details/books/calculus-volume-3">
                https://openstax.org/details/books/calculus-volume-3</url>. You 
                can read the textbook online or download a PDF version. 
                The textbook is also available in print from various retailers 
                if you prefer a physical copy.</p>
        <p>For this lesson, you should read sections <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/3-1-vector-valued-functions-and-space-curves">
            3.1 Vector Valued Functions and Space Curves</url>, and <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/3-2-calculus-of-vector-valued-functions">
            3.2 Calculus of Vector Valued Functions</url>. You should read through the sections carefully, 
            making sure to understand the definitions, examples, and key ideas. 
            You should also work through the exercises at the end of each section 
            to test your understanding and practice applying the concepts. Some of the 
            exercises at the end of the section are assigned in the WP assignments.</p>      
</worksheet>
